post_text:
UNPS Mask Procedure

All UNPS students will be provided with a dual layered UNPS Chief Mask, (red for elementary & black for secondary), upon entry of either the transportation vehicles or the school building. Masks will be collected at each exit door or transportation vehicle at the end of the day. We are asking that students do not take masks home. Each night, the masks from the used bin will be washed/sanitized, machine dried and placed in the clean mask bin to avoid any cross contamination. No outside masks will be allowed. Both staff and students are required to wear masks at all times in the building. Outdoor mask breaks are scheduled in areas that assure proper social distancing. Please be assured that staff will use gloved hands when handling all masks.

Each night, the masks from the used bin will be washed/sanitized, machine dried and placed in the clean mask bin to avoid any cross contamination. No outside masks will be allowed. Both staff and students are required to wear masks at all times in the building. Outdoor mask breaks are scheduled in areas that assure proper social distancing. Please be assured that staff will use gloved hands when handling all masks.

- Call the ACCESSNebraska hotline at 800-383-4278
- Stop by participating food banks that can help fill out applications in person

Grocery Delivery Reminders
Due to increasing concerns regarding COVID-19 the following procedures must be following at the curb-side delivery Wednesday, May 13th from 10:00-1:00. Please;
Limit the number of people in the vehicle to 1 or 2.
Wear a mask if available.
Keep all windows closed throughout pick-up.
Indicate the number of kids in your household by holding up your fingers.
Staff will place groceries in trunks or pickup beds only.
If groceries must go inside the vehicle, UNPS staff will place sacks on the curb and move 6-feet away while you place them in your car.
We appreciate your cooperation with these procedures. We want to continue to distribute goods to the community while keeping everyone safe!

The ongoing COVID-19 emergency has put parents and child care providers alike under tremendous strain. Parents—especially those who must still report to work outside their homes—need access to quality child care services where they know their children will be looked after by licensed, experienced caregivers and educators.

The Nebraska Child Care Referral Network is a newly launched website that can help working parents— particularly those working in critical jobs related to healthcare, food service, and similar roles—to find child care in their area for children from birth to age 12.

Please see the attached flyer for more information about the Nebraska Child Care Referral Network.

Good afternoon! The following is a message from the Nebraska Department of Education:

The United States Congress passed the Coronavirus Aid, Relief, And Economic Security (CARES) Act, which includes one-time relief funding for local school districts, intended to address challenges of providing education during the COVID-19 pandemic.

The Nebraska Department of Education is seeking feedback from all stakeholders to understand local needs as well as potential investments and supports. Please take a moment to complete this short survey:

https://nde.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_efislqh4QDEA1KZ.

Deadline to complete this survey is Monday, May 11, 2020.

Good afternoon! The following is a message from the Nebraska Department of Education:

The United States Congress passed the Coronavirus Aid, Relief, And Economic Security (CARES) Act, which includes one-time relief funding for local school districts, intended to address challenges of providing education during the COVID-19 pandemic.

The Nebraska Department of Education is seeking feedback from all stakeholders to understand local needs as well as potential investments and supports. Please take a moment to complete this short survey:

https://nde.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_efislqh4QDEA1KZ.

Deadline to complete this survey is Monday, May 11, 2020.

NDE.QUALTRICS.COM
2020 Federal CARES Act: Public Feedback Survey

post_text:
A challenge from Ms. Nichols (5th Grade Teacher):

I challenge all of our students to do some self care this weekend!
1. Say something positive about yourself. I am __________.
2.Continue to make yourself better. Practice a skill that may not be easy right now.
3. Take care of yourself-eat well, get enough sleep, shower, and keep a daily routine.
4. Organize something today-your games, books, clothes, or bedroom.
5. Document during this pandemic. Write, draw, photograph, or paint. This is history!
6. Practice kindness.
7. Take a break from screen time-turn off your tv, games, phones, etc
8.JUST BREATHE! Open a window or sit outside your door to get a breath of fresh air!

post_text:
Nebraska School Athletic Association (NSAA)
May1st Transfer List NEW Requirement for high school athletics

ATTN: For any student athletes who are going to be transferring schools, the deadline to do so is May 1st.

The student and his/her legal parent(s) will be required to authorize and give consent to the administration of the school the student is transferring to for the 2020-2021 school year by May 1. The signed consent must be uploaded to the NSAA website in order for the transfer to be recognized. A signed copy of the consent form should be given to the legal parent(s), and the school should retain a copy.
The consent form also provides notice to the student and the legal parent(s), that if the student decides not to transfer after the May 1st deadline, he/she is ineligible for varsity competition for 90 school days at any Nebraska school.

post_text:
Let’s Get Physical!!!

I know it has been tough staying at home so try these a few times a day to stay in shape.

Push-Ups – do 20

Sit-Ups – do 25 rest then 25 more

Leg Raises (on your side) - do 25 with each leg

Leg Raises (on your back) - do 25 with both legs at the same time

Lunges – step forward 10 times with each leg

Jumping Jacks – do 50

post_text:
How can you tell the difference between a cold and the flu?
Because colds and flu share many symptoms, it can be difficult (or even impossible) to tell the difference between them based on symptoms alone. Special tests that usually must be done within the first few days of illness can tell if a person has the flu.
What are the symptoms of the flu versus the symptoms of a cold?
The symptoms of the flu can include fever or feeling feverish/chills, cough, sore throat, runny or stuffy nose, muscle or body aches, headaches and fatigue (tiredness). Cold symptoms are usually milder than the symptoms of the flu. People with colds are more likely to have a runny or stuffy nose. Colds generally do not result in serious health problems.

post_text:
About 20 years ago I was serving as the Chief Negotiator for the Macy Education Association. We had scheduled a meeting which needed to be rescheduled and the announcement went out late. I somehow missed it and showed up for the meeting. Bertram Walker, who was serving as negotiator for the school, also missed the message and showed up. We were the only two there. I hardly knew him but he had a way to make you feel comfortable by just talking about everyday things. These things may seem unimportant but when they pile up they become obstacles to overcome within the school and life, he made me see that. We ended up spending around 45 minutes talking about Macy, school and life in general. I learned more from him in that short time than I ever did in any of my education classes. What I learned from him was real, relevant and having an effect on everything we were doing. Mr. Walker was an asset to the school and the community he will be missed by all.
Joseph Schmidt

post_text:
No school Wednesday, December 18th, 2019.
Bertram Walker, former UNPS Board of Education member, passed away Saturday evening. Mr. Walker dedicated almost 30 years of service as a school board member at UNPS. It is with a heavy heart that we share this news. In honor of his service, the UNPS Board of Education as agreed to host the funeral. Therefore, there will be no school on Wednesday, December 18th. Classes will resume as normal on Thursday. Please extend your condolences to the Walker family during this difficult time.
